<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVIES TO TAPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Anchors Aweigh (KCET Sunday at 3 p.m.) and Kiss Me Kate (at 5 p.m.): A double 
feature of two of director George Sidney's best musicals. 
</P>
<P>
 The Big Street (AMC Monday at 10:30 a.m.) is Lucille Ball's favorite among her 
movies.Here she's in the delightful Damon Runyon tale that casts her as a tough 
Manhattan nightclub singer adored by Henry Fonda's shy busboy; surprisingly, 
the denouement parallels that of "Midnight Cowboy.' Directed by Irving Reis. 
</P>
<P>
 Gas Food Lodging (TMC early Tuesday at midnight), Allison Anders' 1992 film, 
reveals real shrewdness and compassion in her depiction of the ordinary lives 
of a waitress (Brooke Adams) and her two daughters (Ione Skye, Fairuza Balk) -- 
and also a lyrical sense of romance and mystery. 
</P>
