</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 VICTORIA by Knut Hamsun, translated from the Norwegian by Oliver Stallbrass 
(Sun & Moon Press: $10.95; 155 pp.) . Long out of print, this intimate 
depiction of an ill-starred romance contrasts sharply with the Nobel Prize 
winner's epic, "Growth of the Soil." Johannes, the son of a miller, becomes a 
celebrated writer, but his literary success can't remove the stigma of his 
humble birth. He yearns for Victoria, the daughter of a local nobleman, who is 
also a prisoner of her class: Her happiness is sacrificed to the financial 
needs of her aristocratic family. Hamsun examines each character in this 
bittersweet puppet show, shakes his head at their follies, then allows them to 
crumple back into the toy box. 
</P>
</TEXT>
