<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOUR-STAR FILMS; 'LOST HORIZON' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Frank Capra's 1937 film of the James Hilton novel remains a romantic adventure 
classic timelier than ever. Hilton's mythical Shangri-La has long been a 
synonym for an earthly paradise, a refuge from the world's ills.That its story 
is very much an expression of hope from an age of comparative innocence is why 
it works so well. Ronald Colman stars as a noted British diplomat-writer who 
supervises the evacuation of Westerners from a Chinese province in the midst of 
civil war. Taking the last plane out, they wind up not in Shanghai, their 
destination, but on a mysterious trip to the Himalayas. With Jane Wyatt and 
Ronald Colman (both pictured) and Sam Jaffe, John Howard, Thomas Mitchell, 
Margo and others (TNT early Monday at midnight). 
</P>
<P>
 Other four-star films airing this week: 
</P>
<P>
 Way Out West AMC, Sunday, 9 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Rosemary's Baby Bravo, Sunday, 6 and 10 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Great Expectations Bravo, Tuesday, 9:30 a.m. and 7 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 The Sea Hawk TMC, Sunday, 5 a.m.; Wednesday, 9:30 a.m.; Thursday, 4:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Oliver Twist Bravo, Thursday, 3 p.m.; Friday, 9:30 a.m.; TMC Saturday, 5:30 
a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 The Red Shoes Bravo, Saturday, 6 p.m. Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</TEXT>
