<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECORD RACK: IN BRIEF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Steve Hochman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The London Suede, "dog man star," (**) Columbia. If Nirvana's version of "The 
Man Who Sold the World" made you want to know more about early David Bowie, 
this English band's second album will clue you in to the lush sound and 
decadent aura just fine.But if you want the invention and emotion, stick with 
the real thing. Suede's 1993 debut held promise, but this one looks backward 
instead of forward. 
</P>
<P>
 New albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor), two stars (fair), three 
stars (good) and four stars (excellent).  
</P>
<P>
 Steve Hochman 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Recording Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
