<HEADLINE>
<P>
KEEPING YOUR CHRISTMAS TREE FRESH AND SAFE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Stan Kohler, Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Make a fresh cut: Cut off at east one-half inch to open pores clogged by sap. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Put in water: Place tree in a stand that will hold at least one gallon of 
water.If tree is not going into house soon after purchase, it should be stored 
in a bucket of warm water in a cool spot away from wind and sun in warm 
climates and protected from freezing and wind in cold climates. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Water daily: Average tree may consume between a quart and a gallon of water a 
day. Do not let water drop below the cut end of the trunk. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Mini-lights produce minimum heat: The use of smaller lights reduces the drying 
effect on the tree. Always turn tree lights off when leaving house or retiring 
for the night. Do not attempt to repair a worn light set, buy a new set. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Keep away from heat sources: Keep tree away from heating vents, fireplaces, 
television sets, radiators etc. Do not block a door with the tree. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Remove the tree promptly: After Christmas, before the tree dies, remove it 
from the house. Never burn any part of the tree in a wood stove or fireplace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
