<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOYOLA MARYMOUNT PASSES TEST IN 80-71 VICTORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROB FERNAS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Returning to action after a 10-day layoff because of final exams, Loyola 
Marymount's players weren't at their best Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
 But the Lions still met with the approval of Coach John Olive, who could 
complain only so much after his team overcame a sluggish performance to defeat 
foul-plagued Loyola of Chicago, 80-71, in a nonconference game at Gersten 
Pavilion. 
</P>
<P>
 "The 10 days off hurt us," Olive said. "We weren't sharp. We looked a little 
fatigued. The intensity wasn't there like it usually is. But we won the game, 
and that's the bottom line." 
</P>
<P>
 The Lions (5-1), off to their best start since opening the 1989-90 season 6-1, 
committed 23 turnovers and shot 46% from the field. But it was difficult for 
Olive not to smile. In his three seasons at Loyola, he rarely has had the 
luxury of enjoying a victory after a bad game. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's unusual for us," he said. "Hopefully, it's a sign of maturity, of 
finding ways to win when you don't play well." 
</P>
<P>
 Of course, Loyola of Chicago (2-3) did little to take advantage of the 
situation. The Ramblers shot 35% (27 of 78) and committed 30 fouls, resulting 
in Loyola Marymount shooting 41 free throws. The Lions made 29. 
</P>
<P>
 The most critical foul occurred with 7:43 to play when Bernie Salthe, the 
Ramblers' 6-foot-11 center, fouled out on a charging call near the basket. 
Loyola of Chicago Coach Ken Burmeister complained and drew a technical foul, 
resulting in Jim Williamson making one of two free throws to give Loyola 
Marymount a 62-53 lead. 
</P>
<P>
 Williamson, the Lions' sophomore point guard, also did what he was supposed to 
do, making four free throws in the final 1:01 after Loyola of Chicago had cut 
the deficit to 76-71, the smallest it got in the second half. 
</P>
<P>
 Forward Wyking Jones led Loyola Marymount with 22 points and nine rebounds, 
forward Mike O'Quinn had 17 points and four blocked shots, Ime Odouk had a 
game-high 13 rebounds, and Williamson had 12 points and six assists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
