<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE COSTS AND BENEFITS OF NOISY AIRPORT; FLIGHTS OVER BURBANK MAY GIVE 
RESIDENTS HEADACHES, BUT THEY ALSO STIMULATE LOCAL ECONOMY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 We have a few messages for those who run the Burbank-Glendale-Pasadena 
Airport, and for those neighbors who are so fed up with the noise generated by 
its operations. 
</P>
<P>
 Some of us are well-acquainted with the pitfalls of living near an airport: 
having to turn up the volume on your television set so that flight noise won't 
obliterate a vital piece of dialogue; asking the person on the other end of the 
telephone to repeat what was just said; settling in for that one morning of the 
weekend in which you are able to sleep late, only to wind up counting takeoffs 
instead of sheep, and wondering whether the rookie performing touch-and-go 
practices is going to wind up as a roof ornament. 
</P>
<P>
 For its part, Burbank Airport has tried to be a better neighbor. It was the 
first to shift to quieter aircraft. It also has a 10 p.m. to 7 a.m. flight 
curfew. But the roar of aircraft can seem to be an unforgivable intrusion. That 
is why we would urge the Airport Authority to make certain that it has done all 
that it can to reduce the noise associated with each takeoff. But there are 
other realities. 
</P>
<P>
 One is that the airport has won another round in court. Judge Robert H. 
O'Brien has ruled that airport officials complied with state law in the manner 
in which they carried out an environmental impact report. That amounts to a 
major victory in the airport's efforts to build a new and larger terminal that 
will accommodate as many as 10 million passengers annually by 2010. We think 
that new terminal should go forward. 
</P>
<P>
 Burbank Airport is not just a local resource, but a regional one. It continues 
to grow in terms of flight operations because more and more people want to take 
advantage of the option. Its steady contribution to the local economy, in terms 
of jobs and dollars spent, has been a boon during tough recessionary times. 
That fact won't reduce the decibels, but it might increase your tolerance of 
them. We hope so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
