<HEADLINE>
<P>
BETTER SCHOOLS AREN'T BUILT ON PRAYER ALONE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 By placing Andrea Hecht's critique of school prayer ("Private Matter of Prayer 
Just Doesn't Fit in Public Schools," Dec. 11) next to Joyce Sunila's expression 
about violence and other problems in Valley schools ("Count Parent's Confidence 
Among the Fatalities"), The Times did us all a favor by highlighting the key 
educational question before us: Where should we focus our resources in making 
schools the foundation for our communities? 
</P>
<P>
 If the Radical Right has its way, the answer is in school prayer. But this 
will lead only to further splintering and divisiveness in our school system and 
will do nothing to solve the real problems that Sunila addresses. 
</P>
<P>
 The American Jewish Congress believes that if we really want to deal with 
serious educational issues, we should focus our energies on keeping weapons out 
of the hands of schoolchildren, on improving school infrastructures (Sunila and 
her neighbors are working hard just to keep the neighborhood school building 
looking decent), and on improving teacher resources. By making public schools 
an integral and strong part of our communities, with much to offer children, we 
will show the next generation what values we truly stand for. 
</P>
<P>
 CAROL PLOTKIN 
</P>
<P>
 Executive director 
</P>
<P>
 American Jewish Congress 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
<P>
 * I think that, since this is the United States of America, the land of the 
free, students who want to pray should be allowed to do so. 
</P>
<P>
 I do not, however, believe that the students who do not want to pray should be 
ejected from their classrooms while they do it. 
</P>
<P>
 So what I propose is this: Let the praying students take their gods, guardian 
angels, goblins, gremlins, ghosts, devils, witches, sorcerers and magicians and 
leave the classrooms to go stand in a snow drift someplace while they practice 
their illusions of superiority, their indifference to reason, and whatever 
other superstitious nonsense their anxieties and imaginations may conjure. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, the sensible students can simply get on with their education. 
</P>
<P>
 DON RICHARDS 
</P>
<P>
 Van Nuys 
</P>
</TEXT>
