<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: MID-CITY: WILSHIRE; OFFICERS EXCHANGE SQUAD CARS FOR BIKES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE BERESTEIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Two wheels can sometimes be better than four when it comes to patrolling the 
busy Wilshire corridor, as police are finding out.  
</P>
<P>
 Beginning last month, Los Angeles Police Department Officers Blake Budai and 
Steve Crane -- both former squad car patrolmen -- became the Wilshire 
Division's first bicycle officers. 
</P>
<P>
 Pedaling through heavy traffic and down side streets and alleys from 10 a.m. 
to 6:45 p.m., the officers find that increased mobility puts them closer to 
merchants and residents from Koreatown on the east to the Beverly Center on the 
west. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're much more in touch with the community now," said Budai, who covers 20 
to 25 miles a day. "You see a lot more on a bike than you do in a patrol car." 
</P>
<P>
 Two specially equipped mountain bikes costing $1,200 each were provided 
through donations made earlier this year to the Wilshire Community Police 
Council, a fund-raising unit for the division. 
</P>
<P>
 The officers received extensive training, said Capt. Lyman Doster, who 
supervises the unit. Although money for the bikes was donated, the men -- who 
cycle in their spare time -- each paid close to $200 for helmets and other 
personal gear. 
</P>
<P>
 The trial run of the bike unit has yielded good results so far, Doster said. 
Several arrests have already been made by the bike patrolmen who have the 
ability to pedal up silently behind unwary suspects. 
</P>
<P>
 The most spectacular arrest made so far by the bike patrol was the capture of 
a thief in the vehicle he had just stolen. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was about 5 p.m., rush hour, and the guy got stuck in traffic," Budai 
said. "We got the call and were the first unit there. There wasn't even a 
pursuit." 
</P>
<P>
 A squad car could have easily become entangled in the rush-hour snarl. 
</P>
<P>
 Six more Wilshire Division officers have completed bike training, Budai said, 
but the division needs more donations to buy more bikes.  
</P>
<P>
 The Wilshire Community Police Council may be contacted by calling the 
division's senior lead office at (213) 485-4020. LESLIE BERESTEIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
