<HEADLINE>
<P>
EXPLORER REACHES PEAK BEFORE 89TH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Only days shy of his 89th birthday, explorer Norman Vaughn reached the summit 
of the 10,300-foot-high Antarctic mountain that bears his name. 
</P>
<P>
 Vaughn, who turns 89 Monday, and his team spent Friday night atop Mount 
Vaughan, expedition organizers said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1928, Vaughan joined Adm. Richard E. Byrd's South Pole expedition as a 
22-year-old Harvard dropout and became the first American to drive dogs in the 
Antarctic. 
</P>
<P>
 It was Byrd who named the Queen Maud Mountains peak in Vaughan's honor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
